{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_bison_ver01/data/sn83045217/00295860728/1921031301/0840.xml":{"full_text":"1\nFOR AUTO BUSINESS\n0\nImportance of Motor Car in\nEconomic and Social Life of\nNation Emphasized.\nBy H. A. BIGGS\nVim-President Studebaker Corporation.\nThe third largest industry in Amer\nica \u2014and that means the whole world\n\u2014did not attain its place of eminence\nby mere acident or through any seas\nonal or faddish demand for the pro\nduct of its great institutions.\nThe automobile, both passenger and\ncommercial, is an absolute necessity\nof a new era\u2014and it will continue as\na necessity until something newer and\nbetter takes its place. However, up to\nthe present time no one even has an\nInkling of something better.\nThe great majority of the people\nrealize the economic value of the motor\ncar\u2014it would be as impossible to con\nceive of personal and business effi\nciency without the automobile today as\nIt would be to conceive of handling\nmodern business without fast express\ntrains, fast freights, telegraphs or\nlong distance telephones. The motor\ncar has not only become an essential\npart of modern life, but it has been\ngreatly responsible for the develop\nment of the way we live and do busi\nness today. It has. indeed, made pos\nsible the wonderful business achieve\nments which we accomplish in the\ntwelve months of the year.\nBanker Approves Autos.\nJohn G. Lonsdale, president of the\nNational Bank of Commerce, St. Louis,\nis nationally known in the world of\nfinance. His opinion, based on cold,\nunbiased facts, is worthy of special\nnote. Mr. Lonsdale has publicly set\nforth a financial policy which recog\nnizes the motor vehicle as a time-econ\nomy unit. He says:\n\"This is an age of electricity and\ngasoline. Distance is annihilated by\nthe telegraph and telephone. Business\nis transacted not only nationally but\ninternally by wire. Money is trans\nported by telegraphic transfers of\ncredit. If it is a question of hard sur.\nfaced roads and automobiles against\nthe country worn road and the ox cart\nIn the rut, nobody wants to go back\nto the 'old days'. -If the high cost of\nliving is a problem and a man's fixed\nexpense is to be reckened, we must\nhave a time saver, whether it be the\ntelephone, telegraph, the wireless the\nautomobile or gasoline propelled sur\nface car, or the airplane. It makes no\ndifference whether a man is a brick\nlayer, plumber, or banker; if his time\nis worth aii5 'thing ;t is economy to\nlimit his period of transportation.\"\nThe automobile has ceased to be a\nluxury. It might have been called one,\nat the start, like the airplane. But\nthe luxury of yesterday becomes the\nnecessity of today. As Mr. Lonsdale\nso aptly puts it: \"Many years ago\nWhen our forefathers had wooden doors\nand sliding shutters for windows, win\ndow glass was considered a luxury\nonly for the rich, but now it is a neces\nsity even for the poor, letting sunslrne\nnnd happiness flow from without, and\nkeeping within the warmth necessary\nto horrx\u00bb comfort.\"\nPeople have built their lives around\nthe automobile, bought their homes,\nselected their vacation camps and their\nsummer cottages. Businesses have\nbeen developed around the touring car\nand truck as the indispensable vehicle.\nPleasure Profitable.\nAnd furthermore, when you consider\nthe motor car purely from the pleasure\nviewpoint you have a potential demand\nof great proportions. Call it: a 'pleas\nure car' if you will, you must admit\nthat the automobile has been a great\nemancipator. There must be neue\ntime set aside for pleasure in the lives\nof all of us if we aro to maintain our\nusefulness in our work. What is there\nthat gives more return per dollar\nspent in the way of health gh'ing pleas\nure than the automobile. It takes the\nfamily out. of doors and literally\n\"jams fresh air down their throats\"\nand furthermore it enables city folks to\nget out into the country where they\ncan get pure air.\nThink of the pleasure it means to\nthe family living in a crowded city to\npack a tempting lunch and motor out\nInto the country, there to pull up\nalongside some wooded glen and, with\nappetites whetted by the invigorating\nride in the clean air and sunshine, en\njoy a meal that would make a spread\nprepared by a city restau rauteur seem\ntasteless. And the whole trip, for a\nfamily of five, would probably cost less\nthan \"the railroad fare to the same spot,\ntaking into consideration--, the actual\nexpense of operating the car, depre\nciation included. The small expense of\nthe trip may justly be charged to health\ninsurance for the family.\nThe motor car must also be consid\nered as an important educational fac\ntor. I dare say that the motorist\nknows more about the territory sur\nrounding his town or city that the man\nwho doesn't own a car. Anyway, why\nshouldn't he? The motor car takes\n<Emilem of Satisfaction^\nPOWER\nFor its size the Buick Built\nValve-in-Head Motor is the most\npowerful motor on the market, and\nthat's been Buick's reputation for\n20 years. The 1921 Models are quick\non the pick-up and fast on the hills.\nBuicks are backed by a strong factory\nand an old and well established distributor\nso they are safe cars to buy.\nCome in and look them over\u2014they are beauties.\nWESTERN MOTOR CO.\n617 Central Ave. Phone 4303\nhim off the beaten paths\u2014takes him\nout into the open country and shows\nhim the beauties of nature and permits\nhim to visit interesting places that he\nmight otherwise never see. What is\nmore\u2014the motorist goes and comes\nwhen he pleases. He is not dependent\nupon the schedules of train or trolley.\nLinked City and Country.\nThe automobile has brought the city\nto the country, and vice versa. From\nthis both have profited socially and\nfinancially. While we have been talk\ning about good roads, the automftbde\nhas forced them upon us and lessened\nthe cost of farm produce by reducing\nthe cost of transportation. Because\nof motor cars, farmers have acquired\nthe urban habit of going after what\nthey want as soon as they want it.\nNo longer do they allow their wants\nto accumulate, as in the old days.\nThe utility of the automobile on the\nfarm is demonstrated in many wajrs.\nFarmers who live 15 to 30 miles distant\nfrom their market used to consume an\nentire day making the round trip and\nat times, if the day proved unusuallv\nhot, it would be along into the nignt\nbefore the tired horses and men would\nreach home. Today farmers in these\nsame sections start for the market\nearly in the morning and are back on\ntheir farms in a few hours\u2014ready for\na day's work at something else.\nThe farmer has been quick to real\nize that the automobile increased his\nefficiency on the farm, affording him\nmeans of daily visits_ to his neighboring\ncities and forever dispelling the isola\ntion of farm life by reason of its\nstrong appeal to the entire family as\na pleasuraale enjoyment enabling\nthem to visit their neighbors and rela\ntives whenever so disposed. It is no\nUncommon occurence now for neigh\nbors, living 20 or 30 miles apart, to\nexchange evening and Sunday visits\nwhereas, in the old days of the horse\nand buggy, three or four visits a year\nwas considered a rare treat and an oc\ncasion of more than passing interest.\nChildren living on farms may now en\njoy the advantages of the city or con\nsolidated schools. Some member of the\nfamily, or one of the help, drives them\nto school in the morning returning\nlater in the day for the trip back home\n\u2014and everybody's time is conserved.\nWhat is more important just now, the\nautomobile is acomplishing what about\neverything else has failed to do\u2014it is\nkeeping the boys on the farms and\neliminating the desire for exodus to the\ncity.\nEverybody wants, and expects, to\nown an automobile some day--either for\nbusiness or pleasure. There is no need\nfor us to worry about whether it is a\nnecessity or a luxury. Regardless of\nwhat we say or do, or how we argue\nor reason, the automobile will answer\nfor itself.\nConstant Inspection From Raw\nMaterials to Finished Car,\nSays Official.\nBy M. F. WOLLERING.\nVice President of Engineering and Pro\nduction, Studebaker Corporation.\nTo the owner who sits complacently\nbehind the wheel of his car, free from\nthe worry of mechanical troubles, there\nis seldom a thought of what is behind a\ngood car's inbuilt stamina that enables\nit to stand up and give service under\nevery possible road condition, in every\npart of the world.\nQuality never finds its way into an\nautomobile by accident. It is due to\ncertain reasons, to the presence of\nhigh grade materials; skillful engineer\ning; exacting tests in laboratories, in\nthe factory, *>u the road; constant in\nspections throughout the process of\nmanufacture. And these in turn mean\nthat the manufacturer must be big\nenough to have resources and equip\nment enough to make sure that, the\nstandards laid down are rigidly adhered\nto.\nXor can the importance of tradition\nbe over.-estimated Seek the reason for\nany great, long-lived manufacturing\nsuccess and you will find that the con\ncern in question has not only held to\nideals of quality but has possessed the\nfacilities for seeing to it that quality\nwas built into its product. Iu mater\nial, design and workmanship it has\n'made sure.\" This has been Stude\nbaker's experience.\nBegin With Raw Materials.\nSome sage has said that tile training\nof a child should begin with its grand\nparents. In like manner it may be said\nI that the inspection of a car should be\ngin with the raw materials. Not only\ndoes Studebaker specify highest qual\nity materials, but, we check up on all\nour suppliers, subjecting these mater\nials to the most rigid and searching\ntests to make absolutely sure they\nmeasure up to specifications.\nWith us even the smallest bolt re\nceives careful consideration and an in\ndividual material specification made for\nit. Chrome-nickel and chrome-vana\ndiura steels are used on parts where\na combination of toughuess, hardness\nExpects Many Truck\nSales This Season\n\nJ. H. WELLENS.\nJ. H. Wellens, manager of the\nGreat Falls Auto Truck company,\ndealers for the Studebaker Six, the\nCole Aero Eight, and the Day-Elder\ntrucks, believes the oil business in\nMontana in 1921 is to increase motor\ntruck sales greatly.\nThe Great Falls Auto Truck com\npany started business here in May,\n1920, since which time 58 new Stude\nbakers, seven new Coles and four new\nDay-Elder trucks, and about 45 used\ncars have been sold by its sales force.\nThe company is located at 307 First\navenue north. Associated with Mr.\nWellens, the manager, are: II. J. Wel\nlens and P. E. AVenz, salesmen, and\nTom Davidson ,in charge of the ser\nvice department.\nMr. Wellens was for nearly seven\nyears with the Minneapolis branch of\nthe Studebaker organization, and for\nfour years before that was with the\nJ. I. Case company at Racine, Wis.\nAltogether, Mr. Wellens has been in\nthe automobile business 15 years, and\nthough he has had considerable ex\nperience in the mechanical end of the\nbusiness, his specialty is sales promo\ntion. He is particularly optimistic as\nto the amount of business possible in\nhis territory during the ocming spring\nand summer. For the Cole Aero\nEight, he has the northern half of\nMontana, and for the Studebaker and\nthe Day-Elder trucks he has Cascade\nChouteau, northern half of Lewis and\nClark. Teton, Pondera, Glacier, Toole\nand Liberty counties.\nand exceptional fatigue properties are\ndemanded, and the physical properties\nare increased from fifty to seventy\nfive per cent over those obtained by\nthe use of the non-alloy steels. And so\nit goes throughout the car. In each\ncase the material is used that will\ngive the best results in the particular\nfunction it must perform.\nThe Studebaker research and exper\nimental laboratories, unexcelled in the\nindustry, represent an investment of\napproximately $100,000 and employ\n100 skilled men, each holding a college\nor university degree. In the chemical\nlaboratory materials such as steel bar\nstock, brass, bronze, babbit and cast\nQuality Plus Service\nYou Cannot Beat the Combination\nmm\nDay-Elder Worm Drive Trucks\nSIX MODELS\nWheelbase and equipment for all purposes.\nDAY-ELDER growth in five years from small begin\nning to greatest builder in the world of worm drive trucks\ntells the story.\nScientifically proportioned\u2014100% built right trucks\nand the worlds greatest value\u2014 BAR NONE.\nPriced 20 to 33 1-3% under competitors.\ninvestigate\n\nGreat Falls Auto and Truck Co.\nDISTRIBUTORS\nSTUDEBAKER SIXES COLE AERO EIGHTS\n307 First Ave. No. Phone 6408\nGreat Falls, Montana\niron are carefully analyzed and\nchecked with specifications from the\nengineering department. Steering\nknuckles, transmission and rear axle\ngears, steering arms and other vital\nparts are regularly sampled and check\ned in the mechanical laboratory to see\nthat production is always up to stand\nard. Specialized experts test finished\nparts for strength by special machines\nwhich exert crushing, twisting, pulling\nor bending strength sufficient to break\nany finished part.\nExperimental Department.\nIn the metallurgical laboratory, tests\nare made of heat-treated steel under\nmicroscopic enlargements from sam\nples which are taken after each heat\ntreatment. In the research laboratory,\nwhich is fully equipped with scientific\nwork along original lines, the work\nconsists of investigating, analyzing and\ndeveloping new ideas toward determin\ning their relative merits and commer\ncial value.\nThe work of the experimental de\npartment has to do with all new models\nand special apparatus, the inspection\nof a sample of all purchased parts,\nsuch as dies, guages and so on. These\noutside parts, of course, are previous\nly rigidly inspected and checked up by\ntheir makers before delivery to us,\nbut Studebaker engineers take noth\ning for granted. They insist upon a\nthorough inspection under their own\neyes to ascertain whether the work has\nbeen accurate and up to our standards.\nThis department is also used for the\npurpose of conducting road tests to\ncheck up laboratory results under act\nual road conditions.\nAll of these tests are of course sup\nplemented by rigid inspections all along\nthe line while each car is in produc\ntion in the factory. Some idea of how\nthorough and far-reaching these inspec\ntions are may be better understood\nfrom the following figures: In the\nmanufacture of the series 21 Stude\nbaker cars 1120 mechanical operations\nrequire accuracy to the one-thousandth\n(.001) part of an inch, and 360 oper\nations to the one-half thousandth\n(.0005) part of an inch. More than\n680 inspectors are employed to make\nsure that these standards are lived up\nto. Nearl y 9,540 inspections take\nplace in the Studebaker plants before\ncars are permitted to go to a customer.\nName is Asset.\nFrom the foregoing it is plainly evi\ndent that only great resources permit\nof the taking of such precautions to\nmake sure that the finished product\nis as nearly perfect as skilled engin\neering, the finest equipment and the\nbest materials can make it. When\nStudebaker makes a car to fill a cer\ntain demand, many things must be con\nsidered which a smaller organization\nneed not consider. In the first place,\nthe name of Studebaker, known as it\nis all over the world for quality, is a\npriceless business asset. The name\nalone could be capitalized at millions\nof dollars and it would be worth every\ndollar put into it. A name with value\nlike this, known the world over for\nmore than 68 years, must be protect\ned. We must make sure.\nThe first object of the great Stude\nbaker factories is to be sure that its\nproduct, manufactured practically com\nplete in these plants, is good enough to\nbe stamped with the name Studebaker.\nA failure in this respect would be\nfatal to the reputation of this great\nname. It is a source of genuine pride\nwith us that the Series 21 Seudebaker\ncars represent what we consider the\ncrowning achievement among the mod\nels that have borne that name, not\nonly for quality but also for skilled\ndesign, value and that insistence upon\n\"making sure.\"\nSTUDEBAKER HEID\n'Can't Keep America Down,\"\nIs Erskine's Statement on\nBusiness Conditions.\nBy A. R. ERSKINE,\nPresident Studebaker Corporation.\nAmerican business has been under\nseveral major operations, but is now\noff the operating table and recuperat\ning in the convalescent ward. Only\na robust giant could have withstood\nsuch heroic treatment and rallied with\nsuch compartive ease. Business in\nEngland, France, Canada, Argentine,\nJapan, India, Australia and other\ncountries under similar operations is\nnot recuperating as rapidly as Amer\nican business. They have all of our\ntrouble plus adverse balances in for\neign trade and depreciated currencies.\nAmerican business has not whollly re\ncovered, of course, but its afflictions\nof over-production, inflated prices and\nhigh cost of living are practically re\nmoved.\nLiquidation, enforced by the Federal\nReserve banks and buyers' strikes have\nreduced many prices to prewar levels,\nand some below the cost of production.\nWith the exception of coal, steel and\niron, which are still more than 100%\nabove pre-war levels, practically all\nbasic commodity prices are on a valu\nation basis, or below it, and such con\nditions are bound to bring buyers back\ninto the market. When such extremes\nare reached, prices rebound and con\nfidence slowly returns. What we need\nis a stabilization of prices on valua\ntion levels, especially for farm pro\nducts, which are below cost of pro\nduction.\nCan't Keep America Down.\nAmerican business, sustained as it\nis by the natural resources of this mar\nvelously endowed country, cannot be\nkept down permanent^. With our\ngreat crops, unlimited mineral re\nsources, big merchant marine, and\n110,000,000 intelligent, ingenious peo\nple, America can and should be pros\nperous in spite of the world conditions,\nand business will rebound to big vol\nume with surprising recovery. The\nidea of from two to five years of con\ntinued depression besetting this country\nis dangerous to foster, repugnant and\nimpossible, because American industry\nand the spirit of American business\nwill not permit it. The gigantic indus\ntries of America, marvelous in their in\ngenuity, ability and extent, are the\nworkshops of the world, supplying not\nonly our domestic requirements of\npractically ail manufactured goods, but\nthose of the world at large to a de\ngree and extent which no other indus\ntrial nation ever before achieved, or\ncan achieve against our competition,\nbecause of our vastly greater siae.\nThis statement of fact is not made\nboastfully or in derogation of the in\ndustries of other nations, but simply\nto refute skeptical statements of ex\ntended depression. True, the derange\nment in foreign exchanges, with the\ndpreciation of foreign currencies, is an\nobstacle to American exports that\nhampers their fullest development, but\na tremendous export trade will be\ndone in spite of this situation. I am\ntherefore confident of the future pros\np\u00e9rity of American business, and con\nsequently, of the American people.\nWill Recover Quickly.\nSpeaking broadly, the automobile\nbusiness will recover as quickly as\nany and remain, as heretofore, a con\nspicuous figure in American industry.\nAnybody who thinks the automobile\nbusiness has been undermined is badly\nmistaken. It is the third largest of our\nindustries, and will grow instead of les\nsen in importance. The strong com\npanies of the industry, with adequate\nplants and capital and good products,\nwill grow and increase their business.\nThose of us in the automobile business\nbelieve in the recovery of business, the\nfuture of our industry, and the return\nof prosperity this year.\nSEDIMENT TRAP\nMost present day gasoline tanks are\nfitted with a sediment trap, which\nusually is located at the place where\nthe pipe line leaves the tank, Bays W.\nW. Wight, of the T. C. Power Motor\nCar Co. This trap has a wire guase\nscreen and a cup is provided to catch\nforeign matter. The car owner should\nmake it a practice to clean this sedi\nment trap out twice a month during\nactive operation. The present grade\nof motor fuel is not strictly pure and\nforeign matter rapidly accumulates in\nthis catch-all.\nPERFECT MOTOR TRANSMISSION\nTwo inventors of Sisterville, West\nVa., have perfected a transmission\nsystem for motors, which is said to be\nespecially well adapted for automobiles.\nIt is claimed the new invention will\nenable the gearing automatically to\npick up a load on the drive shaft and\nthat it will tend to prevent slipping of\nthe gearing by virtue of the wedge ac\ntion set up.\nat the Show\nSeries 21 Cars\nSeeing is believing! Examine these cars critically. Compare values at\nthe Show, where everything is displayed.\nStudebaker cars are of exclusive Studebaker design\u2014conceived by Studebaker\nengineers and built complete in Studebaker factories.\nStudebaker' s reputation precludes the building of cheap cars or the making of\nsubstitutions to lower costs, and therefore, these cars contain the best-known grades\nof steel, leather, upholstery, finishing paints and enamels, tires and accessories as\nwell as the finest of workmanship.\nLi\nTh\nS\nE\nG\nH\nT\nx\n5-passenger\u201440-horsepower\u2014 112-inch wheelbase\nCord Tire\u00bb Standard Equipment\nTouring, $1485; Landau-Roadster, $1650; Sedan, $2150. Prices L o. K South Bend\n5-passenger\nThe Special-Six\n50-horsepower \u2014119-inch wheelbase\nCord Tit*\u00bb Standard Equipment\nTouring. $1750: Two-Passenger Roadster. $1750; Four -Passenger-Roadster, $1750;\nCoupe. $2650; Sedan. $2750. Pnces L o. b. Detroit\nS\nB\nThe\nx\ng\n7-passenger 60-horsepower 126-inch wheelbase\nCord Tire\u00bb Standard Equipment\nTouring. $215a Price f. o. b. Detroit.\nAll open and closed models are on display at\nGREAT FALLS AUTO AND TRUCK CO.\nPhone 6048\n305 First Avenue North\n\"This is a Studebaker Year\"\nThe best monument a highway\nengineer can build for himself is\na system of Concrete Highways.\nIt will outlive him and back his\ngood judgment for many years.\nPORTLAND CEMENT ASSOCIATION\nSan Fmdm\nChicago Detroit Loa Angeles Parkeroburg Seattle\nDalla\u00bb Helena Milwaukee Pittsburgh Sc. Louts\nDenver Indianapolis Minneapolis Portland, Oreg. Vancouver, B.C.\nDes Moines Kansas City New York Salt Lake City Washington\nWrite for Good Roads Booklet R-3","height":"23016","width":"19176"}}
